Building a song recommender¶

Fire up GraphLab Create¶

In [15]:
import graphlab

Load music data¶

In [16]:
song_data = graphlab.SFrame('song_data.gl/')

Explore data¶

Music data shows how many times a user listened to a song, as well as the details of the song.

Count number of unique users in the dataset¶

In [21]:
users = song_data['user_id'].unique()
In [25]:
len(users)
Out[25]:
66346

Create a song recommender¶

In [26]:
train_data,test_data = song_data.random_split(.8,seed=0)

Simple popularity-based recommender¶

In [27]:
popularity_model = graphlab.popularity_recommender.create(train_data,
                                                         user_id='user_id',
                                                         item_id='song')

PROGRESS: Recsys training: model = popularity
PROGRESS: Warning: Ignoring columns song_id, listen_count, title, artist;
PROGRESS:     To use one of these as a target column, set target = <column_name>
PROGRESS:     and use a method that allows the use of a target.

PROGRESS:     Data has 893580 observations with 66085 users and 9952 items.
PROGRESS:     Data prepared in: 0.743624s
PROGRESS: 893580 observations to process; with 9952 unique items.

Use the popularity model to make some predictions¶

A popularity model makes the same prediction for all users, so provides no personalization.

Build a song recommender with personalization¶

We now create a model that allows us to make personalized recommendations to each user.

In [30]:
personalized_model = graphlab.item_similarity_recommender.create(train_data,
                                                                user_id='user_id',
                                                                item_id='song')

PROGRESS: Recsys training: model = item_similarity
PROGRESS: Warning: Ignoring columns song_id, listen_count, title, artist;
PROGRESS:     To use one of these as a target column, set target = <column_name>

Quantitative comparison between the models¶

We now formally compare the popularity and the personalized models using precision-recall curves.

In [35]:
%matplotlib inline
model_performance = graphlab.recommender.util.compare_models(test_data,
                                                            [popularity_model,personalized_model],
                                                            user_sample=0.05)
